Dear Parents and Guardians,

In order to access your child's email and access Google Classroom, please complete the following steps:

1- Go to mail.google.com, or search for Gmail

2-Put in your child's username. This will be the last two digits of their year of graduation, last name, first initial, @carmarea.org

EXAMPLE=31smithz@carmarea.org

3-use the password "casdmikes" to login. This is the default password if your child has not changed this password.

Please note, only fully virtual students with the blue color designation need to log in to their Google Classrooms tomorrow. Fully virtual students with the gold color designation will need to log in to their Google Classrooms on Thursday. All other students attending in the hybrid mode will start their online work beginning next week. If you have any questions, please contact your school‚Äôs office.

post_text:
Important Information Regarding Tonight‚Äôs Football Scrimmage:

As a school district in the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania, we are required to follow the mandate allowing no more than 250 people in our stadium for the contest tonight. Please understand that both the home and away football teams and their staff, officials, and game workers have to be included in this number. With that, an allotment of tickets have been distributed to each player. Also, an allotment of tickets have been provided to Charleroi. To enter the stadium area tonight, a ticket must be presented so that we can ensure that we abide by the given mandate. The only entrance will be at the gate between the elementary and high school buildings. Please understand that this is not a Carmichaels Area School District rule, but a mandate sent down from our state government. We are hopeful that potential legislation will allow us to alter this mandate in the near future. Thank you for your understanding and your patience as we work through these changes.

Yours Very Sincerely and Respectfully,

Fred Morecraft
Superintendent

post_text: Last week, our district received notification of approval for the ESSER Grant, a school-funding Grant related to the CARES Act. As part of this grant, and in conjunction with other grant-funded sources, our district will now become a one-to-one technology device district. All students within the district will be provided a new, touchscreen Chromebook to promote education in today‚Äôs digital world. Further information regarding distribution of these devices will be forthcoming. In conjunction with this initiative, all district teachers have participated in Google Level 1 training, with several teachers earning their Google Level 1 certification. Moving forward, we are planning professional learning opportunities for students, staff, parents, and the community regarding this new technology.

post_text:
On last Wednesday, parents, teachers, administrators, school board members, and various community members met to establish a ‚ÄúBack to School‚Äù committee to develop a multi-layered plan regarding our return to school in the Fall. Within this committee, nine subcommittees were created to address the varied logistics regarding our return. The committees (listed below) will update their progress through a Google Site, which will be made available to the public in the near future. Additionally, any questions regarding the committee and our return to school can be addressed to the ‚ÄúFrequently Asked Questions‚Äù portion of the Google Site. We believe that through tansparency and collaboration, we can establish a well-developed plan to return that is best for all stakeholders.

Back to School Subcommittees
-Athletics
-Budget/Finance
-Communication
-Curriculum and Instruction
-Food Services
-Health, Satety, and Maintenance
-Special Education
-Technology
-Transportation
text:
On last Wednesday, parents, teachers, administrators, school board members, and various community members met to establish a ‚ÄúBack to School‚Äù committee to develop a multi-layered plan regarding our return to school in the Fall. Within this committee, nine subcommittees were created to address the varied logistics regarding our return. The committees (listed below) will update their progress through a Google Site, which will be made available to the public in the near future. Additionally, any questions regarding the committee and our return to school can be addressed to the ‚ÄúFrequently Asked Questions‚Äù portion of the Google Site. We believe that through tansparency and collaboration, we can establish a well-developed plan to return that is best for all stakeholders.

Back to School Subcommittees
-Athletics
-Budget/Finance
-Communication
-Curriculum and Instruction
-Food Services
-Health, Satety, and Maintenance
-Special Education
-Technology
-Transportation

Class of 2020 ‚Äì Senior Spotlight

Maria Rankin

Maria states high school has always been something that she dreaded would end to soon. She has used every minute that she could to make new friends and learn new things. High school showed what it was to have a passion and have something she was good at. She found that in the band and in the music program. Band helped her become who she is and showed her that she could stand up, help out, and be a leader. Those are qualities she never saw in herself but that Mrs. Walker always saw in her. She was lucky enough to have a good group of people that surrounded her and made sure to push her past her comfort zones. If it was not for them she would not have become involved with the musicals. The musicals really helped her to step out of my shell and become confident. In the fall I will be attending West Virginia University with plans to pursue a career in nursing.

Class of 2020 ‚Äì Senior Spotlight

Abigail Fordyce

Abigail states the pandemic may have taken away her last chance to play softball and the rest of her senior year, but it cannot take away the unforgettable experience and memories she has made in the past four years. She says that the Class of 2020 is truly special and like a huge family and that makes it even harder for them to miss out on these last few months. She says that every experience in the classroom, on the field, and on the peer court have shaped her into the person she is today. She will miss everything and everyone but she will especially miss the volleyball atmosphere and looking up to see Mikes Nation going crazy in the stands. She will never forget the support and love that Carmichaels has shown her throughout her high school experiences. In the fall, she plans to attend Saint Francis University to earn a doctorate degree in Physical Therapy. She will also be a member of the Red Flash Volleyball team!

The Carmichaels Area School District Board of Education regular May 21, 2020 meeting will be held in person at 7 p.m. in the Middle-Senior High Media Center with a work session to start at 6:30 p.m. Due to the COVID-19 ongoing pandemic, and the restrictions on public gatherings, there can only be a max of 25 people in attendance, including board members and administration, at the meeting. Any overflow will be permitted to view the meeting virtually in a separate room. This meeting will also be offered in a virtual platform for those who cannot attend in person. Interested residents who wish to attend this meeting remotely, may do so by contacting Fred Morecraft, Superintendent, prior to 4 p.m. on Thursday, May 21, 2020 at the following email address:
virtualschoolboardmeeting@carmarea.org

You will be provided with a link to attend the virtual meeting prior to the meeting time. Thank you for your understanding in this matter.

shared_text:
Kate DiCamillo
May 14 at 6:36 AM ¬∑

Here in Minnesota, we are doing a statewide, all-ages read of Because of Winn-Dixie.
I cannot even begin to tell you how happy and proud this makes me.
I moved to Minnesota from Florida when I was thirty years old.
I wanted to be a writer, but I hadn‚Äôt written anything.
And then, during a very hard winter--a winter when I was homesick for the warmth of Florida, and feeling very keenly the lack of a dog in my life--I wrote Because of Winn-Dixie.
It was my first book, and the way I see it, everything that has happened to me as a writer has happened because of Winn-Dixie.
So: thank you, Minnesota.
And thank you, teachers, booksellers, librarians, parents, grandparents, kids and readers everywhere.
There is going to be a virtual gathering and discussion around Because of Winn-Dixie on May 20th.
Here is the link: https://zoom.us/webinar/register/WN_rducPyaERA-Z9QZFkLH8pA
I hope you will join us.

post_text: Class of 2020 Graduation Ceremony will be held on Friday, June 5, 2020 at 8:30 PM on the football field. To adhere to current safety guidelines, students and their guests will remain inside their vehicles at all times unless speaking or receiving their diploma. Vehicles must be standard vehicles, no motorhomes or other vehicles that could block the views of others will be permitted. Each senior will be allowed 2 vehicles, one with themselves and their immediate family, and one additional vehicle. There will be live streaming of the event for anyone to watch from home. More information about live streaming will be coming soon. Gates for the event will open at 7:45 PM. There is a mandatory graduation practice on Thursday, June 4 at 10:00 AM. Alternate weather date for the ceremony is June 6, 2020.

Packet pick-up and drop-off will take place on Tuesday, May 5th from 9 am to 1 pm at the Elementary Center, and from 11:00 am to 12:30 pm at the Middle/High School. This packet contains materials for May 5 - May 25. All packets are due on May 26th, as students‚Äô fourth quarter grades are due on May 27. The final packet will be an enrichment packet that can be picked up on May 26.

In a continued effort to emphasize the importance of student participation, term 4 grades will be based upon an average of the firsts three term grades, which will serve as the base grade. All additional assignments for the fourth nine weeks will then impact this term grade. We continue to emphasize the importance of student participation during this time. If you have any questions regarding this information, please contact your child‚Äôs office.

post_text:
PennCFL Stock Market Challenge winners!
Parker Pratt placed 3rd with a 11.94% return and a portfolio value of $111,937. and Esther Schmelzlen placed 8th with a 9.77% return and a portfolio value of $109,768. They competed with 558 students from Greene, Fayette, Washington, Westmoreland and Allegheny counties.
Students were given a hypothetical $100,000 to invest in the Stock Market during a 10 week competition provided by PennCFL.
Congratulations to our young investors!

Thank you Pennsylvania Council on Financial Literacy for this great learning experience!

A Message from the Class of 2020 President:
Class of 2020,

We are living in an unexpected time of uncertainty. The Covid-19 pandemic may have cut our time at Carmichaels Area High School short, but it will never take away our accomplishments. As a class we should not let this be what defines us, we are so much more than that. The class of 2020 is full of talent, potential, and we are destined to do great things. Because of everything you have accomplished, we want to celebrate you through a Senior Spotlight. This is where I need your help, please send an email comprised of a few sentences about your high school experience and your post graduation plans as well as 4-6 pictures of yourself to classof2020@carmarea.org. I know that this may not be the most conventional year, but let‚Äôs make the most of the memories that we were able to make. Stay safe, I can‚Äôt wait to see you all again.

Your friend,
Cole Newland

post_text:
A message from our HS Student Council President, Joshua Hixon, during National Student Leadership Week

"The world may be crazy right now with COVID-19 but we just have to stay positive and keep our eyes on the future.

I'm a senior this year and my senior year got interrupted by the virus but I'm just staying positive and keeping my eyes on the future.

I know we may not be in school and you may not get to see your friends but just stay in contact with each other over social media and before we know it, Coronavirus will be gone.

To my fellow seniors, I hope that everyone has a great rest of the year. I hope to see you all at prom when we have it. Stay positive and safe everyone <3 <3"

#staypositive #thinkofthefuture #thingswillgetbetter #nslw2020

Carmichaels Area School Community,

The Governor has ordered all schools to remain closed for the remainder of the 2019-20 academic year due to COVID-19. Schools are strongly encouraged to provide continuity of education to students.

Although our schools will remain closed, Carmichaels Area School District remains committed to continuing in the education of our students. The district feels it is our duty to continue to support our students and their families. Meals will continue on schedule as well. Stay tuned for more details, and keep checking our FAQ page on our website.

We will get through this... Together!
Stay Safe and Stay Healthy

Can‚Äôt wait to go back to school
I‚Äôm going to soon lose my cool

Attention Carmichaels Families:

We wanted to make you aware of some resources that relate to online learning.

Atlantic Broadband is offering internet service to low-income families at no cost for a 15/2 Mb connection for 2 months and it is $9.99/month after that - Anyone who wants to sign-up will need to contact customer care at 1-888-536-9600 or visit:
https://atlanticbb.com/keeping-customers-safe-and-connected-covid-19

Also, a Wifi connection access point has been been set up in the parking lot between the Middle/High School and the Elementary Center for student use. It's SSID is "HSMS_student". Most students have the password. If needed please contact your building offices. This is a filtered internet connection. Please be advised to use the social distancing protocols enacted by our government and local authorities.

Stay Safe and Stay Healthy!

Attention Carmichaels Area School Community:

The Department of Education (PDE) announced today all schools in the commonwealth will remain closed through at least April 6 as a result of the COVID-19 response efforts. The closure order could be extended beyond April 6 if necessary to save lives and stop the spread of COVID-19.

Under the new timeline, school buildings would reopen on April 7 for two days to allow school administrators, teachers and other staff time to prepare classrooms, set up cafeterias, schedule transportation and arrange other business operations. Students would return to school on April 9, unless extending the closure is needed in response to the situation with the virus at that time.

Thank you for your flexibility in this matter.

Stay Safe and Stay Healthy

Carmichaels Area School Community:

Please understand that we are working to finalize plans that will give our parents/guardians and students more guidance on the procedures for delivery of education, along with being able to provide meals for the children of the district.

Be on the lookout for notification via our "One Call" system, email, and social media outlets for details on how to access Google Classroom, packet delivery/distribution, and food options.

These are unprecedented times, but understand that we are trying to do our best to provide for our children. Please try to be flexible and understanding in our efforts.

Please be safe, and look out for those in need, especially our elderly community members and those with compromised immune systems.

More information will follow soon.

post_text: Mrs. Adamson's third grade class enjoyed the Riverhounds SC Sub In For Gym Class program today during Mrs. Steinhoff's gym class. James Meara, Riverhounds Academy Director, Jason Rice, Riverhounds Academy Coach, along with Christian Mori, Riverhounds Academy player and an 11th grader at Carmichaels Area High School, lead students through a unique spin on physical education classes by integrating soccer-centric drills into a fun period of teamwork, exercise and smiles. This program, which is offered at no cost to the schools, is intended to introduce soccer training to communities that may have not yet been exposed to the beautiful game. Thank you to Mrs. Steinhoff and Mr. Berry for bringing this program to Carmichaels Elementary School for the week.

post_text:
PA Game Commission Game Warden Brandon Bonin visited Carmichaels Area High School students to discuss State Game Lands regulations and Wildlife Diseases like Chronic Wasting Disease, EHD, and West Nile Virus affecting our state's wildlife resource.

Game Warden Bonin provided information on career opportunities for employment with the PA Game Commission along with the skills and training he has received to carry out all aspects of his job as Game Warden. He also showed the students an injured Black Vulture that he was taking to an Animal Hospital later that day. What a unique experience for the students!

We want to thank Game Warden Bonin for taking the time out of his busy schedule to share his experience with our students!

Attached photo 1: (l-r) Chloe Mitchell, Faith Willis, Ainsley Chadwick, Brooke Watters, and Game Warden Brandon Bonin

MIKES ACADEMIC LEAGUE JV TEAM MAKES TAKES CARE OF BUSINESS GOING 2‚Äì0 AT MATCH 4 HOLDING THEIR SPOT IN THE PLAYOFFS.

The Carmichael‚Äôs JV Academic Team finished the regular season strong going 2‚Äì0 and earning the 4th seed in the Tri-County Academic League playoffs.

The JV team won both matches against Albert Gallatin and Jefferson Morgan earning 4 team points out of a possible 4 points.

The JV team defeated Albert Gallatin 43 ‚Äì 38; Jack Chadwick led the team with 23 points; Jonah Smith contributed 10 points; Lauren Dobish added 2 points. The team earned an additional 8 points in their two lightning rounds.

The JV team defeated Jefferson-Morgan by one question 37 ‚Äì 36 qualifying for the playoffs by that single question; Jack Chadwick led the team with 16 points; Jonah Smith contributed 6 points; Jacob Fordyce earned 5 points; and Lauren Dobish added 2 points. The team earned an additional 8 points in their two lightning rounds.

The JV team will square off against the top-seeded Uniontown in the first round of the playoffs scheduled for Wednesday March 4th 2020.

Mikes Nation had the privilege of "Best Seats In The House" on Valentine's Day for the Pittsburgh Ballet Theatre's presentation of "Beauty and the Beast".

According to the Pittsburgh Ballet Theatre, "Beauty comes from within. So does the nature of the Beast. See both sides of the story in Beauty and the Beast. The classic tale weaves a tender love story between the gnarled trees of the enchanted forest. Audiences are offered a glimpse at unexpected romance, heartbreak and the power of love through striking scenery and stunning neoclassical choreography.
